  <h2 class="mb-4">Key Terms You Must Understand</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>
            <h6>NAV (Net Asset Value)</h6>
            <p>
            NAV represents the price of one unit of a mutual fund.
            It changes daily based on the market value of the fund’s holdings.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
    <h6>CAGR (Compound Annual Growth Rate)</h6>
    <p>
      CAGR shows the average annual return of the fund over a specific period.
      It helps compare long-term performance across funds.
    </p>
</li>
<li>
    <h6>AUM (Assets Under Management)</h6>
    <p>
      AUM is the total amount of money invested by all investors in the fund.
      A higher AUM often indicates investor trust and stability.
    </p>
</li>
<li>
    <h6>Expense Ratio</h6>
    <p>
      This is the annual fee charged by the fund house to manage the fund.
      Lower expense ratios are better for long-term investors.
    </p>
 </li>
 <li>
    <h6>Exit Load</h6>
    <p>
      Exit load is a fee charged if you withdraw your investment before a
      specified period. It encourages long-term investing discipline.
    </p>
</li>
<li>
    <h6>Minimum Investment</h6>
    <p>
      The minimum amount required to start investing in a fund.
      Mutual funds are accessible even with small amounts.
    </p>
    </li>
</ul>

  <p class="text-muted mt-4">
    These metrics together help you make informed and confident investment decisions.
